messages.content:
I see another potential issue. Look at this code:

```cpp
Value *Op0 = ZExted;
if (auto *OI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(OtherOperand))
  Builder.SetInsertPoint(OI->getNextNode());
Value *Op1 = Builder.CreateTrunc(OtherOperand, SmallTy);
Builder.SetInsertPoint(&I);
```

If `OtherOperand` is an instruction, we set the insertion point to after that instruction. Then we create the truncate. Then we set the insertion point back to `&I`. This means the truncate will be inserted after `OI`, not before `I`. That might be OK, but what if `OI` dominates `I`? Actually, `OI` might not even be in the same basic block as `I`.

Actually, `OtherOperand` is an operand of `I`, so it must dominate `I`. So `OI` (if it's an instruction) must be before `I`. Setting the insertion point to `OI->getNextNode()` means the truncate will be inserted right after `OI`, which is before `I`. That's probably OK.

But what if `OtherOperand` is a phi node? `dyn_cast<Instruction>` would succeed, but `getNextNode()` on a phi node? Actually, phi nodes don't have a next node in the usual sense. They're at the beginning of the block. `getNextNode()` might return the first non-phi instruction in the block. That might be OK.

